1.INTRODUCTION

1.1.DATA DESCRIPTION

From f1 to f162 the features express distances. f163 is the distance of the oxygen atom in the molecule to a designated point in 3-space.This is also called OXY-DIS. f164 is also known as OXY-X, X-displacement from the designated point. f165 is also known as OXY-Y, Y-displacement from the designated point. f166 is also known as OXY-Z, Z-displacement from the designated point.

1.2.STEPS OF THIS ASSIGNMENT

Step 1

I clustered the instances of this data set given, which is Musk1. I proposed 2 distance measures for computing similarity between the instances, which are euclidean and manhattan. For each measure alternative that i selected, i clustered according to kmeans and hierachical. To work with distances, i used k-medoids approach

Step 2

I calculated the distance of its instances to each cluster centroid. Due to the fact that i have 92 cluster centroids, the data matrix i calculated includes 476 rows and 92 columns. Because i have 476 observations and for each observation i calculated the distance to each cluster centroid. I repeated it four times for kmeans-Euclidean,kmeans-Manhattan,hierchical-Euclidean,hierachical-Manhattan.

Step 3

I represented the bag as the average of its instances to the cluster centroids. I used lasso logistic regression on the bag level representation for classifying bags.

CLUSTERING APPROACHES FOR EACH DISTANCE MEASURE ALTERNATIVE

K means clustering is a clustering algorithm where i attempt to classify my dataset into k number of clusters. Each data is mapped into the cluster with its nearest mean. Therefore, there is no need to find distance for k means. As you see from above, i found euclidean and manhattan distance, respectively. But these will not be used for k means clustering because of the concept of k means clustering. On the other hand, hierchical clustering is a clustering algorithm which mapped into a hierarchy showing similarities and dissimilarities. Therefore, in this clustering algorithm i will use distances that i calculated above which are euclidean distance and manhattan distance.

OPTIMAL K VALUE

fviz_nbclust_silh<-fviz_nbclust(musk, kmeans, method = "silhouette") # finds optimal number of clusters
plot(fviz_nbclust_silh)

fviz_nbclust_wss<-fviz_nbclust(musk, kmeans, method = "wss") # finds optimal number of clusters
plot(fviz_nbclust_wss)

You can see 2 plots above. The first plot represents average silhoutte width versus number of clusters. As you see optimum number is determined as 2. Actually, accoridng to some reserach and articles done, the optimum number of k is generally 2 when you want to observe this performance measure, which is average silhoutte width. It is actually the disadvantage of this performance criteria. As an example of it, optimum number of cluster is 2 for Musk1 data as you see, which accepts and shows the accuracy of this academic research. The second plot shows total SSE and number of clusters. As you see, as the number of clusters increases, total sse decreases.

It is decided to train lasso logistic regression on the bag level representation for classifying bags.

I used milr package and milr function for this case.

Transform instance level representation to bag level representation

STEP2

#KMEANS APPROACH WITH EUCLIDEAN DISTANCE

kmeans_musk_euc_medoids<-kmeans_musk_euc$medoids

head(kmeans_musk_euc$data)

distanceMatrix_euc_kmeans <- matrix(NA, nrow=dim(musk)[1], ncol=dim(kmeans_musk_euc$medoids)[1])

for(i in 1:nrow(kmeans_musk_euc$medoids)) {
    distanceMatrix_euc_kmeans[,i] <- sqrt(rowSums(t(t(musk)-kmeans_musk_euc$medoids[i,])^2))
}

dim(distanceMatrix_euc_kmeans)

head(distanceMatrix_euc_kmeans)

#KMEANS APPROACH WITH MANHATTAN DISTANCE

kmeans_musk_man_medoids<-kmeans_musk_man$medoids

distanceMatrix_man_kmeans <- matrix(NA, nrow=dim(musk)[1], ncol=dim(kmeans_musk_man_medoids)[1])

for(i in 1:nrow(kmeans_musk_man_medoids)) {
    distanceMatrix_man_kmeans[,i] <- rowSums(abs(t(t(musk)-kmeans_musk_man_medoids[i,])))
    
}

dim(distanceMatrix_man_kmeans)

head(distanceMatrix_man_kmeans)

#HIERCHICAL APPROACH WITH EUCLIDEAN DISTANCE

clusterCut_musk_euc <- cutree(hclust_musk_euc, 92)

cluster_centroid_euc = function(i,musk,clusterCut_musk_euc) { ind=(clusterCut_musk_euc==i) colMeans(musk[ind,]) }

centroid_euc_hier<-sapply(unique(clusterCut_musk_euc),cluster_centroid_euc,musk,clusterCut_musk_euc)

distanceMatrix_euc_hierach <- matrix(NA, nrow=dim(musk)[1], ncol=dim(centroid_euc_hier)[2])

for(i in 1:ncol(centroid_euc_hier)) { distanceMatrix_euc_hierach[,i] <- sqrt(rowSums(t(t(musk)-centroid_euc_hier[i,])^2)) }

dim(distanceMatrix_euc_hierach)

head(distanceMatrix_euc_hierach)

#HIERCHICAL APPROACH WITH MANHATTAN DISTANCE

clusterCut_musk_man <- cutree(hclust_musk_man, 92) #92 snfa ayrld

cluster_centroid_man = function(i,musk,clusterCut_musk_man) { ind=(clusterCut_musk_man==i) colMeans(musk[ind,]) }

centroid_man_hier<-sapply(unique(clusterCut_musk_man),cluster_centroid_man,musk,clusterCut_musk_man)

distanceMatrix_man_hierach <- matrix(NA, nrow=dim(musk)[1], ncol=dim(centroid_man_hier)[2])

for(i in 1:ncol(centroid_man_hier)) {
    distanceMatrix_man_hierach[,i] <- rowSums(abs(t(t(musk)-centroid_man_hier[,i])))
}

dim(distanceMatrix_man_hierach)

head(distanceMatrix_man_hierach)

STEP3

#KMEANS-EUCLIDEAN

aggregate_kmeans_euc<-aggregate(distanceMatrix_euc_kmeans, list(kmeans_musk_euc$clustering), mean)

head(aggregate_kmeans_euc)

#KMEANS-MANHATTAN

aggregate_kmeans_man<-aggregate(distanceMatrix_man_kmeans, list(kmeans_musk_man$clustering), mean)

head(aggregate_kmeans_man)
